# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2020-colorado-wildfires
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The **2019–20 Australian bushfire season**, also known as the **Black Summer**, was one of the most intense and catastrophic fire seasons on record in Australia.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Exceptionally dry conditions, a lack of soil moisture, and early fires in Central Queensland led to a premature start to the bushfire season from June 2019.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Over ten thousand fires burnt, mainly in the south-east of the country, until March 2020.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The most severe fires hit from December 2019 to January 2020.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fires burnt more than 24 million hectares (59 million acres; 240,000 square kilometres; 93,000 square miles) destroyed over 3,000 buildings, and directly killed 33 people.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Bushfire smoke was responsible for an additional 417 deaths.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] An estimated three billion terrestrial vertebrates, mostly reptiles, were killed or displaced.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Some species may have been driven to extinction.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In all affected states, air quality dropped to dangerous levels, and smoke moved across the Southern Ocean to impact weather conditions in other continents.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Carbon emissions exceeded 700 million tonnes.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Rescue and recovery efforts were immense.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] States of emergency were declared across various regions of New South Wales (NSW) and the north-east to east of Victoria, which were the areas most impacted.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] NSW alone recorded 11,774 fires; six percent of the state burned.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Methods of community damage control included total fire bans and strict evacuation orders.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Australian Defence Force was mobilised to provide manpower and logistical support, and international crews were brought in from New Zealand, Singapore, Canada and the United States.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] An air tanker, helicopters and fire trucks crashed in rescue efforts, resulting in the deaths of several crew members.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The last major fire in Victoria was contained on 27 February 2020, and all fires in New South Wales were extinguished by 2 March.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The total economic loss was estimated being at least $100 billion, far and away the costliest natural disaster in Australian history.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Tourism sector revenues fell by $2.8 billion.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] There was considerable debate regarding the underlying cause of the intensity and scale of the fires, including the role of fire management practices and climate change.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fires attracted significant international attention.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] An estimated $500 million was donated by the public, international organisations, public figures and celebrities for victim relief and wildlife recovery.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Convoys of donated food, clothing and livestock feed were sent to affected areas.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In eastern and north-eastern Victoria large areas of forest burnt out of control for four weeks before the fires emerged from the forests in late December, taking lives, threatening many towns and isolating Corryong and Mallacoota.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A state of disaster was declared for East Gippsland.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Significant fires occurred in the Adelaide Hills and Kangaroo Island in South Australia.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Moderately affected areas were south-eastern Queensland and areas of south-western Western Australia, with a few areas in Tasmania and the ACT being mildly impacted.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 12 November 2019, catastrophic fire danger was declared in the Greater Sydney region for the first time since the introduction of this level in 2009 and a total fire ban was in place for seven regions of New South Wales, including Greater Sydney.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Illawarra and Greater Hunter areas also experienced catastrophic fire dangers, and so did other parts of the state, including the already fire ravaged parts of northern New South Wales.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The political ramifications of the fire season have been significant.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 14 January 2020, 18.626 million hectares (46.03 million acres) was burnt or is burning across all Australian states and territories.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Ecologists from the University of Sydney estimated 480 million mammals, birds, and reptiles were lost since September with concerns that entire species of plants and animals may have been wiped out by bushfire, later expanded to more than a billion.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Since the start of the season, the ongoing bushfires have destroyed 2,176 homes, as well as 48 facilities and more than 2,000 outbuildings in New South Wales alone.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Twenty-five people were confirmed to have been killed in New South Wales since October.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The latest fatality reported was on 23 January 2020 following the death of a man near Moruya.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In New South Wales, the fires burnt through more land than any other blazes in the past 25 years, in addition to being the state's worst bushfire season on record.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] NSW also experienced the longest continuously burning bushfire complex in Australia's history, having burnt more than 4 million hectares (9,900,000 acres), with 70-metre-high (230 ft) flames being reported.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In comparison, the 2018 California wildfires consumed 800,000 hectares (2,000,000 acres) and the 2019 Amazon rainforest wildfires burnt 900,000 hectares (2,200,000 acres) of land.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Whereas these bushfires are regarded by the NSW Rural Fire Service as the worst bushfire season in memory for that state, the 1974 bushfires were nationally much larger consuming 117 million hectares (290 million acres; 1,170,000 square kilometres; 450,000 square miles).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] However, due to their lower intensity and remote location, the 1974 fires caused around A$5 million (approximately A$36.5 million in 2020) in damages.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In December 2019 the New South Wales Government declared a state of emergency after record-breaking temperatures and prolonged drought exacerbated the bushfires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Due to safety concerns and significant public pressure, New Year's Eve fireworks displays were cancelled across New South Wales including highly popular events at Campbelltown, Liverpool, Parramatta, and across Sydney's Northern Beaches, and as well in the nation's capital of Canberra.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As temperatures reached 49 °C (120 °F), the New South Wales Premier Gladys Berejiklian called a fresh seven-day state of emergency with effect from 9am on 3 January 2020.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 23 January, a Lockheed C-130 Hercules air tanker crashed at Peak View near Cooma while waterbombing a blaze, resulting in the death of the three American crew members on board.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] It was one of eleven large air tankers brought to Australia for the fire season from Canada and US.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] An investigation is underway by the ATSB to determine the cause of the accident.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Reaching the crash site proved difficult due to the active bushfires in the area.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The crash site was located in dense bushland, and spanned approximately one kilometre.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] To describe emerging fire trends the study by Lucas and others defined two new fire weather categories, "very extreme" and "catastrophic".
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The number of "extreme" fire danger days generally increases 5-25% by 2020 for the low scenarios and 15-65% for the high scenarios.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In April 2019 a group of former Australian fire services chiefs warned that Australia was not prepared for the upcoming fire season.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] They called on the next prime minister to meet the former emergency service leaders "who will outline, unconstrained by their former employers, how climate change risks are rapidly escalating".
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In August 2019 the federally funded Bushfire and Natural Hazards CRC published a seasonal outlook report which advised of "above normal fire potential" for southern and southeast Queensland, the east coast areas of New South Wales and Victoria, for parts of Western Australia and South Australia.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In December 2019, the Bushfire and Natural Hazards CRC updated their advice of "above normal fire potential".
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Australian National University reported that the area burned in 2019–2020 was "well below average", pointing out that 30 million hectares less than the Australian annual average burned that year.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] More specifically, the early part of the season (2019) had "near average" burn area, whereas the area burned in the late part of the season (2020) was "unusually low".
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The NSW statutory Bush Fire Danger Period normally begins on 1 October and continues through until 31 March.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In 2019–20, the fire season started early with drought affecting 95 percent of the state and persistent dry and warm conditions across the state.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Twelve local government areas started the Bush Fire Danger Period two months early, on 1 August 2019, and nine more started on 17 August 2019.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 6 September, the northern parts of the state experienced extreme fire dangers.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At the Port Macquarie suburb of Crestwood a fire started on 26 October from a dry electrical storm.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Water bombers were delayed the following day in attempts to bring the fire burning in swampland to the south west of Port Macquarie under control.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A back burn on 28 October got away from New South Wales Rural Fire Service (NSWRFS) volunteers after a sudden wind change pushing the fire south towards Lake Cathie and west over Lake Innes.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Port Macquarie and surrounding areas were blanketed in thick smoke on 29 October with ongoing fire activity over the following week caused the sky to have an orange glow.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] During this time the Lindfield Park fire burning in dry peat swamp flared up and threatened homes at Sovereign Hills and crossed the Pacific Highway at Sancrox.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On the Carrai Plateau west of Kempsey, a fire burnt in wilderness areas where locked up and poorly maintained fire trails made combating it difficult.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] This fire joined up with the Stockyard Creek fire and together with the Coombes Gap fire and swept east towards Willawarrin, Temagog, Birdwood, Yarras, Bellangary, Kindee and Upper Rollands Plains.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Land around Nowendoc and Yarrowich was also burnt.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] This fire burnt more than 40,000 hectares (98,842 acres), destroying numerous homes and claiming the lives of three people.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] North-west of Harrington near the Cattai Wetlands a fire started on 28 October, this fire threatened the towns of Harrington, Crowdy Head and Johns River as it burnt north towards Dunbogan.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] This fire claimed one life at Johns River, where it also destroyed homes, and burnt more than 12,000 hectares (29,653 acres).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At Hillville, a fire grew large due to hot and windy conditions, resulting in disorder in the nearby town of Taree, to the north.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Buses were called in early to take students home before the fire threat became too dangerous.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 9 November, the fire reached Old Bar and Wallabi Point, threatening many properties.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The following two days saw the fire reach Tinonee and Taree South, threatening the Taree Service Centre.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Water bombers dropped water on the facility to protect it.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire briefly turned in the direction of Nabiac before wind pushed it towards Failford.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Other communities affected included Rainbow Flat, Khappinghat, Kooringhat and Purfleet.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A spot fire jumped into Ericsson Lane, threatening businesses.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At Dingo Tops National Park a small fire turned into a massive bushfire emergency as it impacted the small village of Bobin; numerous homes and the Bobin Public School were destroyed in the fire.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Fourteen homes were lost on one street in Bobin.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The NSWRFS sent out alerts to people in Killabakh, Upper Lansdowne, Kippaxs, Elands, and Marlee to monitor conditions.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] 2019 Rally Australia, planned to be the final round of the 2019 World Rally Championship, was a motor racing event scheduled to be held in Coffs Harbour across 14–17 November.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A week before the rally was due to begin, the bushfire began to affect the region surrounding Coffs Harbour, with event organisers shortening the event in response to the deteriorating conditions.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] With the situation worsening, repeated calls from competitors (most of which were European-based) to cancel the event prevailed with the event cancelled on 12 November.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In late December 2019, fires started on both sides of the Pacific Highway around the Coopernook region.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] They burnt 278 hectares (687 acres) before they were brought under control.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A large fire in November at Gospers Mountain in the Wollemi National Park burnt over 496,976 ha (1,228,050 acres) and threatened homes in the Hawkesbury and Lithgow areas.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire was projected to burn towards the Central Coast and potentially threaten properties in Wisemans Ferry and other townships.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In an attempt to protect the Blue Mountains from the Gospers Mountain bushfire, firefighters commenced a large backburn on 14 December from the corner of Mt Wilson and Bells Line of Road.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The backburn quickly grew out of control, jumping across Mt Wilson Road and threatening houses in Mount Wilson.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 15 December, the escaped backburn impacted Mount Tomah, Berambing and Bilpin.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire destroyed numerous houses and buildings in this area and spread into the Grose Valley.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 19 December the RFS Mt Wilson Backburn escape impacted on the Darling Causeway between Mount Victoria and Bell, it later jumped the Darling Causeway and impacted the Grose Valley and the fire would be split into two fires: Grose Valley fire and Gospers Mountain fire.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 21 December, a catastrophic day, the Mt Wilson Backburn (the southern part of which was now designated the "Grose Valley fire") impacted Mount Victoria, Blackheath, Bell, Clarence, Dargan and Bilpin with resultant destruction of dozens of homes.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On the same day the escaped RFS Mt Wilson Backburn fire moved towards Kurrajong.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Further buildings were destroyed as a result of backburning operations in Blackheath along Evans Lookout Road.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By 15 December, the "Gospers Mountain fire" had grown to 350,000 hectares (860,000 acres).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] There have been persistent myths that the "Gospers Mountain Fire" was the largest fire from a single ignition source in Australian history.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Gospers Mountain Fire was a result of multiple ignition points, the majority of which, were the result of large scale strategic backburning operations that escaped control.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The estimated total area burnt by escaped backburning around the Gospers Mountain Fire is over 130,000 hectares.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Whilst the original ignition may have been caused by lightning, the subsequent, separate ignitions caused by RFS backburning contributed greatly to the spread of the fire and the impacted the ability of the RFS to deploy sufficient resources to defend communities.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 12 November, under Sydney's first ever catastrophic fire conditions, a fire broke out in the Lane Cove National Park south of Turramurra.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Under strong winds and extreme heat the fire spread rapidly, growing out of control and impacting the suburban interface across South Turramurra.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] One house caught alight in Lyon Avenue, but was saved by quick responding firefighters.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As further crews arrived and worked to protect properties, a C-130 Air Tanker made several fire retardant drops directly over firefighters and houses, saving the rest of the suburb.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire was ultimately brought under control several hours later, with one firefighter injured suffering a broken arm.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Because of the bushfires occurring in the surrounding regions, the Sydney metropolitan area suffered from dangerous smoky haze for several days throughout December.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On some days, the air quality was eleven times the hazardous level, making it even worse than New Delhi's.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The conditions were likened to "smoking 32 cigarettes" by Associate Professor Brian Oliver, a respiratory diseases scientist at the University of Technology Sydney.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 10 December the fire impacted the south-western Sydney suburbs of Nattai and Oakdale, followed by Orangeville and Werombi, threatening hundreds of houses and resulting in the destruction of one building.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire continued to flare up sporadically, coming out of the dense bush and threatening properties in Oakdale and Buxton on 14 and 15 December.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire moved south-east towards the populated areas of the Southern Highlands and impacted the townships of Balmoral, Buxton, Bargo, Couridjah and Tahmoor in far south-western Sydney.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Substantial property losses occurred across these areas, in particular multiple fire trucks were overrun by fire, with several firefighters taken to hospital and two airlifted in critical condition.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Later that night, two firefighters were killed when a tree fell onto the road and their tanker rolled, injuring three other crew members.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The situation deteriorated on 21 December when the fire changed direction and attacked Balmoral and Buxton once more from the opposite side, with major property losses in both areas.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On New Year's Eve there were fears of this fire impacting the towns of Mittagong, Braemar, and surrounding areas.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 31 December, a grass fire broke out in the sloped woodlands of Prospect Hill, in Western Sydney, where it headed north towards Pemulwuy along the Prospect Highway.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire impacted a large industrial area and threatened numerous properties before being brought under control by 9:30pm.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Approximately 10 hectares (25 acres) and a number of historic Monterey pine trees were burnt.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Sydney City fireworks display was allowed to continue with a special exemption from fire authorities, despite protests.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Despite warnings from authorities, numerous fires were sparked across Sydney as a result of illegal fireworks, including a blaze which threatened properties at Cecil Hills in Sydney's south west.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 4 January, Sydney's western suburb Penrith recorded its hottest day on record at 48.9 °C (120.0 °F) making it the hottest place on Earth at the time.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 5 January, a fire broke out in bushland at Voyager Point in Sydney's south-west, spreading rapidly under a strong southerly wind and impacting numerous houses in Voyager Point and Hammondville.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As the fire moved north, authorities closed the M5 Motorway due to smoke conditions and prepared for the fire to impact the New Brighton housing estate.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Firefighters on the ground assisted by numerous waterbombing aircraft held the fire south of the motorway and prevented any property losses, containing the fire to 60 hectares (150 acres).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In late October, a number of fires started in remote bushland near Lake Burragorang in the Kanangra-Boyd National Park south-west of Sydney.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Due to the extreme isolation of the area and rugged inaccessible terrain, firefighters struggled to contain the fires as they began to spread through the dense bushland.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] These multiple fires ultimately all merged to become the Green Wattle Creek fire.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire continued to grow in size and intensity, burning towards the township of Yerranderie.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Firefighters undertook backburning around the town whilst helicopters and fixed wing aircraft worked to control the spread of the fire.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire passed Yerranderie but continued to burn through the national park towards south-western Sydney.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 5 December under severe weather conditions, the fire jumped the Lake Burragorang and began burning towards populated areas within the Wollondilly area.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 19 December, the fire continued east towards the Hume Highway (resulting in its closure for several hours), impacting the township of Yanderra.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Over the following days as the fire continued to progress to the south east, both Yerrinbool and Hill Top were threatened by the fire.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As well as expanding to the south and east, the fire also spread in a westerly direction, headed towards Oberon.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Oberon Correctional Centre was evacuated in anticipation of the advancing fire impact along its western flank.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 2 January, the fire hit the popular and historic Jenolan Caves area, destroying multiple buildings including the local fire station.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The centrepiece of the precinct, Jenolan Caves House, was saved.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A blaze on the South Coast started off at Currowan and travelled up to the coastline after jumping across the Princes Highway, threatening properties around Termeil.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Residents in Bawley Point, Kioloa, Depot Peach, Pebbly Beach, North Durras and Pretty Beach were told to either evacuate to Batemans Bay or Ulladulla or stay to protect their property.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 2 January 2020, the Currowan fire was burning between Batemans Bay in the south, Nowra in the north, and east of Braidwood in the west.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire had burnt more than 258,000 hectares (640,000 acres) and was out of control.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Currowan fire had merged with the Tianjara fire in the Morton National Park to the south west of Nowra; and the Charleys Forest fire had grown along the fire's western flank; and on the fire's southern flank, the fire had merged with the Clyde Mountain fire.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By 26 December, the Clyde Mountain fire was burning on the southern side of the Kings Highway, into the Buckenbowra and Runnyford areas.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Around 4 am on 31 December, the fire had crossed the Princes Highway near Mogo, and the highway was closed between Batemans Bay and Moruya.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Around 7 am on 31 December, the fire impacted the southern side of Batemans Bay, causing the loss of around ten businesses and damage to many others.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire also crossed the Princes Highway in the vicinity of Round Hill and impacted the residential suburbs of Catalina, as well as beach suburbs from Sunshine Bay to Broulee.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Residents and holiday makers were forced to flee to the beaches.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On the 23 January this fire escalated back to emergency level as the blaze roared towards the coastal town of Moruya, a town largely unaffected by bushfires in recent weeks.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At nearby Lake Conjola, numerous homes were lost as the embers jumped across the lake, landing in gutters and lighting up houses.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On one street there were only four houses still standing.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 2 January 2020, at least two people died and a woman was missing.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Isolated hamlets of Bendalong and Manyana and Cunjurong Point were additionally ablaze, with holiday-makers evacuated on 3 January 2020.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 6 January 2020, all were still without power.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 5 January 2020, in the Bega Valley Shire, the border fire that started in north-eastern Victoria was burning north into New South Wales towards the major town of Eden, and had impacted the settlements of Wonboyn and surrounding areas including Kiah, Lower Towamba and parts of Boydtown.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Part of the fire was burning in inaccessible country and continued to head in a north-westerly direction towards Bombala as well as northerly to just south of Nethercote.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire had burnt more than 60,000 hectares (150,000 acres) and was out of control.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 30 December, the Green Valley fire burning east of Albury near Talmalmo (which had started the day prior) developed into an unprecedented fire event for the Snowy Valleys as a result of extreme local conditions.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The smoke plume rose to an estimated 8,000 metres (26,000 ft) and developed a pyro-cumulonimbus cloud, becoming a firestorm.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The result was extreme, the wind was described by crews on the ground as in excess of 100 km/h (62 mph), with spot fires starting over 5 km (3.1 mi) ahead of the main fire front.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Firefighters described what they believed to be a tornado generated by the fire storm, which began flattening trees and flipped a small fire vehicle.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The tornado then impacted a crew of firefighters working to protect a property, flipping their tanker over and trapping the crew inside, who were then overrun by fire.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] One firefighter was killed with multiple others injured, with one airlifted to Melbourne and two to Sydney.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Dunns Road fire was believed to have been started by a lightning strike on 28 December in a private pine plantation near Adelong.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In the Snowy Valleys local government area, by 2 January 2020 the Dunns Road fire had burnt south of the Snowy Mountains Highway in the Ellerslie Range near Kunama.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Over 130,000 hectares (320,000 acres) was burnt and the fire was out of control.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The NSWRFS issued an evacuation order to residents in the Batlow and Wondalga areas.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Residents and visitors to the Kosciuszko National Park were evacuated and the national park was closed.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] 155 inmates from the Mannus Correctional Centre near Tumbarumba were evacuated.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 3 January 2020, the Dunns Road fire burnt from Batlow into Kosciuszko National Park, burning much of the northern part of the park.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire caused significant damage, severely damaging the Selwyn Snow Resort, destroying structures in the town of Cabramurra and almost completely destroying the heritage-listed precinct (and birthplace of skiing in Australia) of Kiandra.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Kiandra's historic former courthouse was left with only its walls standing after a fire so hot that the glass and aluminium in the windows melted.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A number of high country huts, including Wolgal Hut and Pattinsons Hut near Kiandra, were also feared to have been destroyed.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By 11 January three fires had merged – the Dunns Road fire, the East Ournie Creek, and the Riverina's Green Valley fire – and had created a 600,000-hectare (1,482,632-acre) "mega-fire", burning south of the Snowy Mountains.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 23 January, a Lockheed C-130 Hercules large air tanker crashed near Cooma while waterbombing a blaze, resulting in the death of the three American crew members on board.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 21 November, lightning strikes ignited a series of fires in East Gippsland, initially endangering the communities of Buchan, Buchan South and Sunny Point.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 20 December, the Marthavale-Barmouth Spur expanded, greatly endangering the community of Tambo Crossing.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The first day of two-day cricket tour match between a Victoria XI and New Zealand in Melbourne was cancelled due to extreme heat conditions.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 30 December, there were three active fires in East Gippsland with a combined area of more than 130,000 hectares (320,000 acres), and another in the north-east of the state near Walwa heading south-east towards Cudgewa.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] An evacuation warning was issued for the East Gippsland town of Goongerah, which is surrounded by high-value old growth forests, as well as Cudgewa.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On the same day, a fire broke out in the Plenty Gorge Parklands, situated in Melbourne's northern suburbs between Bundoora, Mill Park, South Morang, Greensborough and Plenty.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Fires reached the town of Mallacoota by around 8 am AEDT on 31 December 2019.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At 11 am AEDT 31 December, fires had begun to approach the vacation town of Lakes Entrance.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Despite the recommendation that large portions of East Gippsland be evacuated, approximately 30,000 holiday makers chose to remain in the region.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Approximately 4,000 people, including 3,000 tourists, remained in Mallacoota as the fire began making its closest approach to the town, cutting off roads in the process; Mallacoota had not been issued with an evacuation warning on 29 December.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 3 January, approximately 1,160 people from Mallacoota were evacuated on naval vessels HMAS *Choules* and *MV Sycamore*.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Emergency Management Commissioner Andrew Crisp stated that 780,000 hectares (1,900,000 acres) had burnt including 100,000 hectares (250,000 acres) near Corryong in the state's north-east and that fifty fires were burning.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 3 January, Premier Andrews said two people were confirmed dead from the East Gippsland fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 6 January Premier Andrews said that bushfires had burnt through 1.2 million hectares (3 million acres) in Victoria's east and north-east and that 200 homes were confirmed lost.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 13 January, two bushfires were burning at emergency level in Victoria despite milder conditions, one about 8 km east of Abbeyard and the other in East Gippsland affecting Tamboon, Tamboon South and Furnel.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 23 January, there were still 12 fires burning in Victoria, the strongest in East Gippsland and the north-east.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Buldah fire in East Gippsland was at watch and act level and the rest were on advice level.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Most of the 44 fires sparked by dry lightning were quickly dealt with by firefighters.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Heavy rain in the Melbourne region brought little relief to bushfire-affected regions.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Premier Daniel Andrews said that the rains could bring new dangers for firefighters, including landslides.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 30 January, four days of hot weather were forecast for Victoria, New South Wales and South Australia bringing high fire danger with several uncontrolled bushfires still burning.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 7 September 2019 multiple out of control blazes threatened townships across south-eastern and northern Queensland, destroying eleven houses in Beechmont, seven houses in Stanthorpe, and one house at Mareeba.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On the following day the heritage-listed lodge and cabins at the iconic Australian nature-based Binna Burra Lodge were destroyed in the bushfire that consumed residential houses in Beechmont the previous day.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A large fire impacted the Peregian Beach area on 9 September, on the Sunshine Coast, severely damaging ten houses.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In December 2019 Peregian Springs and the surrounding areas came under threat by bushfires for the second time in a couple of months.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] No homes were confirmed lost in this bushfire.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Due to deteriorating fire conditions and fires threatening homes across the state, on 9 November a State of Fire Emergency was declared across 42 local government areas across southern, central, northern and far-northern Queensland.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 11 November a fire started in the Ravensbourne area near Toowoomba, which burnt through over 20,000 hectares (49,000 acres) of bush across several days, destroying six houses.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At 8 am the air quality in Brisbane reached unprecedentedly poor levels (Woolloongabba PM2.5 238.8 μg/m3).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Queensland's chief health officer, Dr Jeanette Young, urged residents to stay indoors and to not physically exert themselves.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 13 November a water bombing helicopter crashed while fighting the blazes threatening the small community of Pechey.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] While the Bell 214 helicopter was completely destroyed, the pilot walked away with minor injuries.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 23 November the state of fire emergency was revoked and extended fire bans were put in place in local government areas that were previously affected under this declaration.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 6 December a house fire broke out in Bundamba and quickly spread to nearby bushland and was placed under a watch and act alert by the Queensland Fire and Emergency Services that afternoon.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The following day, after worsening conditions, the fire was upgraded to an emergency warning and began to threaten homes in the local community.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire destroyed a shipping container filled with fireworks, and residents within the 3-square-kilometre (1.2 sq mi) exclusion zone were ordered to evacuate.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 8 November a bushfire broke out in forestry to the west of the township of Jimna, causing Queensland Fire and Emergency services to issue a "watch and act" alert.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire caused the evacuation of the entire town.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 11 November 2019 an emergency bushfire warning was issued for Port Lincoln in the Eyre Peninsula, with an uncontrolled fire traveling towards the town.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The South Australian Country Fire Service ordered ten water bombers to the area to assist 26 ground crews at the scene.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] SA Power Networks disconnected power to the town.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A large fire broke out on Yorke Peninsula on 20 November 2019 and threatened the towns of Yorketown and Edithburgh.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] It destroyed at least eleven homes and burnt approximately 5,000 hectares (12,000 acres).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire was believed to have started from a sparking electrical transformer.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A Boeing 737 water-bombing aircraft from New South Wales in addition to South Australian Air Tractor AT-802s were used to protect the town of Edithburgh.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 20 December fires took hold in the Adelaide Hills, and near Cudlee Creek in the Mount Lofty Ranges.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Initial south-easterly winds put the towns of Lobethal and Lenswood in the line of the fire, and by the next morning the winds had changed to north-north-west, threatening other towns.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fires killed one person, more than 70 houses were destroyed, as well as over 400 outbuildings and 200 cars.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Fires are still burning and the yearly Christmas celebrations at Lobethal were cancelled.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Also on 20 December, an out-of-control bushfire took hold near Angle Vale, starting from the Northern Expressway and burning through Buchfelde and across the Gawler River.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At 11:07 am ACDT the fire was burning under catastrophic weather conditions and an emergency warning was issued for Hillier, Munno Para Downs, Kudla, Munno Para West and Angle Vale.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Another emergency warning was issued on 3 January for a fire near Kersbrook.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At its largest extent, the warning area overlapped with areas that a few days earlier had been in warnings for the Cudlee Creek fire.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Water bombers delivered 21 loads in just over an hour before darkness fell, and 150 firefighters on 25 trucks plus bulk water carriers and earthmoving equipment limited the advance of the fire to 18 hectares (44 acres).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On Kangaroo Island starting in the Flinders Chase National Park, the Ravine bushfire burnt in excess of 15,000 hectares (37,000 acres) and a bushfire emergency warning was issued on 3 January 2020 as the fire advanced towards Vivonne Bay and the town of Parndana was evacuated.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 4 January it was confirmed at least two people died.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 6 January 2020 approximately 170,000 hectares (420,000 acres), representing about a third of the island, had been burnt.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Fires remained burning out of control, with firefighters working to contain and control fires before potentially hot windy weather scheduled for later in the week.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Following fire damage to a water treatment plant, residents were asked to conserve water and some water was carted into island towns.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] There were concerns for the future of threatened wildlife, such as glossy black cockatoos, Kangaroo Island dunnarts, and koalas.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Authorities stated that any koalas taken to the mainland for treatment cannot return to the island in case they bring diseases back with them.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Two bushfires burnt in Geraldton on 13 November, damaging homes and small structures.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A fire broke out in Yanchep at 2:11 pm on 11 December, immediately triggering an emergency warning for Yanchep and Two Rocks.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire led to a service station exploding.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 12 December, temperatures in excess of 40 °C (104 °F) exacerbated the fire, and the emergency warning area doubled including parts of Guilderton and Brenton Bay further north.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 13 December, increased temperature conditions resulted in the fire burning in excess of 5,000 hectares (12,000 acres), with the fire front over 1.5 kilometres (0.93 mi) in length.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 13 December 2019, the emergency warning area stretched from Yanchep north to Lancelin over 40 km (25 mi) away.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By 16 December, the fire was considered contained and the alert downgraded to watch and act.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Approximately 13,000 hectares (32,000 acres) were burnt; only two buildings were damaged, both within the first day of the fire starting.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In December fires in the region around Norseman blocked access to the Eyre Highway and the Nullarbor and caused the highways of the region to be blocked, so as to prevent any recurrence of the 2007 death of truck drivers on the Great Eastern Highway.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Between 26 December 2019 and 1 January 2020, as a result of a lightning strike, a fire tore through 40,000 hectares (99,000 acres) of land in Stirling Range National Park in the southwest of the state, burning more than half of the park.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The pyrocumulus cloud from the fires could be seen 80 km (50 mi) south in Albany.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By New Year's Day 2020 a crew of 200 firefighters brought the fire back to advice level without any loss of life or major property damage (a park ranger hut and hiking tracks were destroyed).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] However, conservationists raised concerns for the potential loss of rare and unique flora and fauna that live in the park, which contains over 1500 such species within its boundaries, including a rare population of quokkas (one of few in mainland Western Australia).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A local politician, firefighters, farmers and tourism operators called on Western Australian Emergency Minister Fran Logan to invest in local firefighting assets for the area in order to make sure the tourist destination was properly protected.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In late October 2019, four bushfires were burning near Scamander, Elderslie and Lachlan.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Emergency warnings were issued at Lulworth, Bothwell and Lachlan.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A large fire near Swansea also burnt over 4,000 hectares (9,900 acres).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Lightning strikes subsequently started multiple fires in Southwest Tasmania.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 20 December 2019, a fire was started in the north east, which spread to 15,000 hectares (37,000 acres) and destroyed one home; a man was charged with starting the fire.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Two fires continued to burn in January 2020.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A fire in the Fingal Valley, in north-eastern Tasmania, started on 29 December, and a fire at Pelham, north of Hobart, started on 30 December.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 16 January 2020 the Fingal fire had burnt over 20,000 hectares (49,000 acres) and the Pelham fire over 2,100 hectares (5,200 acres).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In the Australian Capital Territory (ACT), the national capital Canberra was blanketed by thick bushfire smoke on New Year's Day from bushfires burning nearby in New South Wales.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] That day the air quality in the capital was the worst of any city in the world, at around 23 times the threshold to be considered hazardous.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Conditions continued the next day, and Australia Post stopped postal deliveries in the ACT to keep workers safe from smoke.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The first death directly linked to the poor air quality was also recorded on 2 January.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] An elderly women had been travelling from Brisbane to Canberra by plane, when she exited the plane onto the smoke-flooded tarmac, she suffered respiratory distress and then died.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 2 January 2020, the ACT declared a state of alert; that was extended on 12 January as the merged Dunns Road fire burnt seven kilometres (four miles) from the Territory's south-west border.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] From at least 6 January a bushfire near Hospital Hill in the Namadgi National Park had started; it was extinguished on 9 January.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 22 January a bushfire started in Pialligo Redwood Forest; it reached emergency level threatening Beard and Oaks Estate.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The next day a second bushfire started, the Kallaroo Fire, which later during the day merged with the Redwood Forest fire forming the Beard Fire; the fire jumped the Molonglo River and threatened the suburbs of Beard, Harman and Oaks Estate as it burnt 424 hectares (1,050 acres).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire destroyed 1 facility, 4 outbuildings and 3 vehicles.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 27 January a bushfire in the Orroral Valley in the Namadgi National Park started.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] ACT Emergency Services Minister Mick Gentleman reported, on behalf of the Department of Defence, that the fire had been started by a landing light on a Defence helicopter, while it was conducting routine aerial reconnaissance and ground clearance work to support local firefighters.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By the morning of 28 January the fire had grown to 2,575 hectares in size and was 9 kilometres from the town of Tharwa.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] An emergency warning was declared for Tharwa and the southern suburbs of Canberra just after 1:30pm AEST on 28 January.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Chief Minister Andrew Barr described the fire as the biggest threat to Canberra since the 2003 Canberra bushfires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Northern Territory went through a relatively average annual bushfire season with respect to area of land burnt, in comparison to the scale of bushfires witnessed in other areas of Australia.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Despite this, approximately 6.8 million hectares (17 million acres) was burnt, an area which contributed significantly to the total area burnt by bushfires in the nation.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Five homes were lost to bushfires in the Territory.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] While the full extent of the current bushfires is yet to be measured, there have been a number of large scale bushfires recorded in Australian history.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The widespread 1938-9 fires in Victoria, NSW, South Australia and the ACT similarly gained international headlines when the fires entered the Sydney suburbs, as did the 1994 eastern seaboard fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The 1851 Black Thursday bushfires shocked colonial Australia with their ferocity, burning a quarter of what is now Victoria (around five million hectares).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Lesser known is that about 117 million hectares, or 15 per cent of Australia's land mass, experienced fire in the summer of 1974–5.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] NSW was again badly affected, and three people killed, however the fires were mainly in sparsely populated inland areas.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In mid-December 2019, a NASA analysis revealed that since 1 August, the New South Wales and Queensland bushfires had emitted 250 million tonnes (280 million short tons) of carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 2 January 2020, NASA estimated that 306 million tonnes (337 million short tons) of CO2 had been emitted.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By comparison, in 2018, Australia's total carbon emissions were equivalent to 535 million tonnes (590 million short tons) of CO2.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] While the carbon emitted by the fires would normally be reabsorbed by forest regrowth, this would take decades and might not happen at all if prolonged drought has damaged the ability of forests to fully regrow.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In December 2019, the air quality index (AQI) around Rozelle, a west suburb of Sydney, hit 2,552 or more than 12 times the hazardous level of 200.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The level of fine particle matters, known and measured globally as PM2.5, around Sydney was also measured at 734 micrograms (0.01133 gr) or the equivalent of 37 cigarettes.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 1 January 2020, the AQI around Monash, a suburb of Canberra, was measured at 4,650, or more than 23 times hazardous level and peaked at 7,700.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On New Year's Day 2020 in New Zealand, a blanket of smoke from the Australian fires covered the whole South Island, giving the sky an orange-yellow haze.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] People in Dunedin reported smelling smoke in the air.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The MetService stated that the smoke would not have any adverse affects on the weather or temperature in the country.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The smoke moved over the North Island the following day, but began breaking up and was less intense than over the South Island the previous day; meanwhile, South Pacific winds South Pacific Ocean dissipated the smoke over the South Island.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The smoke affected glaciers in the country, giving a brown tint to the snow.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 5 January 2020, more smoke wafted over the North Island, turning the sky in Auckland orange.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By 7 January 2020, the smoke was carried approximately 11,000 kilometres (6,800 mi) across the South Pacific Ocean to Chile, Argentina, Brazil, and Uruguay.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fires resulted in agricultural losses of over AUD 5 billion, destroying livestock, crops, wildlife and agricultural infrastructure across vast areas.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Chris Dickman, a fellow of the Australian Academy of Science from the University of Sydney, estimated on 8 January 2020 that more than one billion animals were killed by bushfires in Australia; while more than 800 million animals perished in New South Wales.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The estimate was based on a 2007 World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) report on impacts of land clearing on Australian wildlife in New South Wales that provided estimates of mammal, bird and reptile population density in the region.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Dickman's calculation had been based on highly conservative estimates and the actual mortality would therefore be higher.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The figure provided by Dickman included mammals (excluding bats), birds, and reptiles; and did not include frogs, insects, or other invertebrates.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Other estimates, which include animals like bats, amphibians and invertebrates, also put the number killed at over a billion.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Ecologists feared some endangered species were driven to extinction by the fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Though bushfires are not uncommon in Australia, they are usually of lower scale and intensity that only affect small parts of the overall distribution of where species live.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Animals that survived a bushfire could still find suitable habitats in the immediate vicinity, which was not the case when an entire distribution is decimated in an intense event.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Besides immediate mortality from the fires, there were on-going mortalities after the fires from starvation, lack of shelter, and attacks from predators such as foxes and cats that are attracted to fire-affected areas to hunt.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On Kangaroo Island, Australia's third largest island and known as Australia's "Galapagos Island", a third of the island was burnt.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Large parts of the island are designated as protected areas and host animals such as sea lions, penguins, kangaroos, koalas, pygmy possums, southern brown bandicoots, Ligurian bees, Kangaroo Island dunnarts and various birds including glossy black cockatoos.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] NASA estimated that the number of dead koalas could be as high as 25,000 or about half the total population of the species on the island.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A quarter of the beehives of the Ligurian honey bees that inhabited the Island were believed to have been destroyed.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Both the Kangaroo Island dunnart and Kangaroo Island subspecies of the glossy black cockatoo are endangered and are only found on Kangaroo Island.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Before the fires, there were only less than 500 Kangaroo Island dunnarts and about 380 Kangaroo Island glossy black cockatoos.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Australian magpies, which are known to have the ability to mimic the calls of other birds and animals, were so frequently exposed to the sirens from fire trucks and ambulances caused by the bushfires that a magpie in Newcastle was captured on video mimicking the sound of emergency sirens.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The two primary firefighting agencies for New South Wales, Fire and Rescue NSW and the NSW Rural Fire Service, formed the bulk of the primary response to the fires, mobilising thousands of firefighters and several hundred firefighting vehicles.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] They were heavily supported by the NSW National Parks and Wildlife Service and the Forestry Corporation of NSW, who hold jurisdiction over national parks and forests across the state.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Additional local firefighting resources were also utilised from agencies such as Air Services Australia and Sydney Trains.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Despite the substantial loss of property and loss of life, firefighters have so far managed to save over 16,000 structures from direct fire impact in addition to countless lives.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] With brush-tailed rock-wallabies and much of the indigenous wildlife population in parts of New South Wales were left without food or water, the NSW National Parks and Wildlife Service airdropped approximately 1,800 kilograms (4,000 lb) vegetables on the known habitats.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A joint operation by the NSW National Parks and Wildlife Service and NSW Rural Fire Service was mounted to protect the critically endangered Wollemia pines growing in Wollemi National Park.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Fire retardant was dropped from air tankers, and an irrigation system was installed on the ground by specialist firefighters, who were lowered into the area by winches from helicopters.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 24 December 2019, the Morrison Government announced that volunteer firefighters employed in the Commonwealth public service would be offered at least 20 working days paid leave.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 29 December 2019, it announced that volunteer firefighters who have been called out for more than 10 days would be able to receive financial compensation.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 4 January 2020, it announced that it would lease four waterbombing planes including two long-range DC-10s and two medium-range for use by state and territory governments.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 5 January 2020, the Prime Minister announced the establishment of the National Bushfire Recovery Agency, funded initially with A$2 billion, under the control of former Australian Federal Police Commissioner, Andrew Colvin.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 5 December 2019, the Australian Defence Force (ADF) commenced *Operation Bushfire Assist* to support state fire services in logistics, planning, capability, and operational support.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 1 January 2020, the ADF deployed additional military staff establishing the Victorian Joint Task Force 646 (Army Reserve 4th Brigade) and the following day the New South Wales Joint Task Force 1110 (Army Reserve 5th Brigade).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 3 January 2020, HMAS *Choules* and MV *Sycamore* evacuated civilians from Mallacoota bound for Westernport.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 4 January 2020, following a meeting of the National Security Committee, the Morrison Government announced a compulsory call-out of Army Reserve brigades to deploy up to 3,000 reserve personnel full-time to assist with in the Operation.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Additionally, Defence announced that it would deploy HMAS *Adelaide* to support other Navy ships in evacuations and relief, as well additional Chinook helicopters and military transport aircraft to RAAF Base East Sale.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The same day, Chinook helicopters evacuated civilians from Omeo; and Spartan aircraft evacuated civilians from Mallacoota on 5 January.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 1 December 2019 WWF-Australia launched the "Towards Two Billion Trees" plan to aid the koala bushfire recovery.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] It aims to stop excessive tree-clearing, protect the existing trees and forests, and restore native habitat that has been lost.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The ten-point plan for the next ten years foresees to grow 1.56 billion new trees and save 780 million trees.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Political figures from outside Australia including Donald Trump, Cory Booker, Hillary Clinton, Al Gore, Bernie Sanders, Greta Thunberg, and Elizabeth Warren all publicly commented about the fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Some of the aforementioned people have also donated or raised funds.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 4 January 2020, Queen Elizabeth and the Duke of Edinburgh sent a message of condolence to Governor-General David Hurley, sending their "thoughts and prayers to all Australians at this difficult time".
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The Queen indicated in her message that she was "deeply saddened" to hear of the fires and their devastating impact on the country, and expressed her thanks to emergency service workers.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 8 January 2020, Prince Charles issued a video message expressing his despair at the "appalling horror" of the fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Four deployments totalling 87 Canadian firefighters were sent through the Canadian Interagency Forest Fire Centre.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] It was the first time since 2009 that Canadian personnel were deployed to Australia.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The Canadian government also sent a CC-17 plane of the Royal Canadian Air Force with 15 personnel on 27 January to further aid with transport and provide airlift support.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The government of Fiji deployed the Fiji Military Forces humanitarian assistance and disaster relief platoon and engineers to assist in the bush fire rehabilitation.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 6 January, French President Emmanuel Macron stated he could help out with the bushfires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A team of five French firefighting experts arrived in Australia on 9 January in order to determine possible options for French and European support.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 15 January, the Japanese government sent two C-130 aircraft of the JASDF, along with 70 other Self-Defense Force personnel to assist in transport and other efforts in combating the bushfires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The aircraft left Komaki Air Base and flew to RAAF Base Richmond in New South Wales the next day.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 5 January, Malaysia offered its assistance through a statement by Deputy Prime Minister Wan Azizah Wan Ismail.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 13 January, Malaysia officially deployed over forty firefighters to assist with the bushfires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Twenty others from government agencies would also be involved with the mission.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Over fifty New Zealanders were deployed to Australia in both direct fire fighting and support roles.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] In January 2020, New Zealand also deployed elements of the Royal New Zealand Air Force and New Zealand Army including three NH90 helicopters, two Army combat engineer sections, and a command element.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A specialist six person animal disaster response team were deployed by non-profit Animal Evac New Zealand on 8 January to New South Wales, assisting with wildlife rescue and supported by SAFE.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The team was the first international specialist animal rescuers to arrive and included vets, animal management officers as well as animal disaster and technical animal rescue experts.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A second team of four arrived on 13 January.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The teams partnered with local wildlife centres to successfully rescue and relocate several injured animals. as well as advising residents in fire danger zones on their animal evacuation plans.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The Government of Papua New Guinea offered to send 1,000 military and other personnel to Australia to assist with the response to the bushfires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Australia accepted 100 Papua New Guinea Defence Force personnel.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The Philippine Red Cross pledged to donate $100K to Australia, while various Filipino personalities pledged support for the victims of the bush fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The women-led Teduray people of Maguindanao initiated a sacred rain-making ritual for Australian victims, calling on the fire goddess Frayag Sarif's intercession to bring rain to the country.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Singapore deployed two Chinook helicopters and 42 Singapore Armed Forces personnel stationed at Oakey Army Aviation Centre to RAAF Base East Sale in Victoria.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The United Arab Emirates sent 200 volunteers from the Emirates Red Crescent to help fight the fire, including Emirati astronaut Sultan Al Neyadi.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A Twitter campaign and hashtag #mateshelpmates was launched by the Dubai Expo 2020 aiming to raise donations to help those affected by the fires in Australia.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] To increase awareness, Burj Khalifa in Dubai, the world's tallest tower, lit up in solidarity with Australia.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Twenty firefighters from the United States Department of the Interior were deployed to Australia to help combat the fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Fire fighters from other parts of the US also helped with the fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 23 January, three US firefighters died in the crash of a C-130 fire fighting aircraft.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Australia is one of the most fire-prone continents on earth, and bushfires form part of the natural cycle of its landscapes.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Nonetheless, the political nature of many of the crisis and its associated issues has also resulted in the circulation of large amounts of disinformation regarding the causes of the fire activity, at the neglect of credible scientific research, expert opinion, and previous government inquiries.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The major cause of ignition of fires during the 2019–20 fire crisis in NSW and Victoria is reported to be lightning strikes.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] According to the ABC, arson has been of little impact – accounting for around 1% of NSW blazes and 0.3% of Victorian blazes by 18 January 2020.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A likely contributor to the bushfire crisis was the ongoing drought in eastern Australia – the most severe on record for some fire affected areas.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Exacerbating the effects of diminished rainfall in this drought has been a record breaking run of above average monthly temperatures, lasting 36 months to October 2019.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The combination of heat and drought caused critical low fuel moisture content, with Victoria Country Fire Authority Response Controller Gavin Freeman stating that the "underlying dryness" of the bush has led to exceptionally high fire danger.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) stated that on account of projected future climate change, hot days will become more frequent and hotter (very high confidence), and the time in drought is projected to increase over southern Australia (high confidence).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] In October 2019 David Littleproud, the Australian Minister for Water Resources, stated that he "totally accepts" the link between climate change and drought in Australia, as someone who has experienced it first hand.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The crisis has led to calls for more action to combat climate change.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] That said, the Morrison government has received some criticism on its 2030 emission reduction targets.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] In the midst of the crisis, conservative politicians and media blamed a lack of prescribed burning and fire break management, although such assertion has subsequently been heavily criticized and disproven by scientific experts.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Accompanying this was the assertion that environmental groups were responsible for the crisis by inhibiting prescribed burning, despite environmental groups holding relatively negligible political power compared to the Liberal and National parties.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Furthermore, the amount of prescribed burning in southeastern Australia has been stated to have increased in recent years, following the recommendation for increased prescribed burning from the 2009 Black Saturday Royal Commission.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Experts suggested that prescribed burning has been more difficult to achieve given recent trends towards warmer and dryer conditions.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Experts have also cast skepticism on the effectiveness of fuel reduction treatments, citing research that suggests that prescribed burning does little to stop bushfire and save property in south east Australia, with climate and weather conditions having primary influence.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Of particular note, the damaging Currowan fire burnt though a large area of Morton National Park subject in 2017 to one of the largest prescribed burns ever successfully conducted in NSW.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The NSW Rural Fire Service referred numerous individuals to the NSW Police; 24 people were charged with arson, allegedly starting bushfires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Approximately one percent of the land burnt in NSW, and 0.03 percent in Victoria, was attributed to arson.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Queensland police reported that 114 fires "were found to be deliberately or maliciously lit".
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Incorrect reporting and social media claims about the extent of the fires, its precedents and causes, and matters like funding of fire fighting services have been circulated during the fire season.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Media outlets of differing political allegiances have also disputed each other's coverage.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A number of maps giving an exaggerated impression of Australia's fires have gone viral online, and have been published by major news outlets.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Maps showing "hotspots" were spread online as comprehensive fire maps, giving an exaggerated impression of the extent of fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Photographs of previous Australian bushfires were also being wrongly published as current. and maps that exaggerate the extent of the fires, or include both past and present fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Incorrect reports were disseminated that the New South Wales Government, led by Premier Gladys Berejiklian, had cut funding to fire services.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] NSW Rural Fire Service Commissioner Shane Fitzsimmons, in response to the funding cut claims, stated "that it is rubbish, it is misinformation, it's being misrepresented and I think it is disgracefully being misrepresented here today".
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] He also stated that "not only has our budget not been cut, we are enjoying record budgets.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] We have got more money today than we have ever had before in the history of the organisation".
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Debate and controversy continue to surround previous funding cuts to fire management agencies, with other reports noting recent funding cuts to the National Parks and Wildlife Service, which is responsible for the planning and enforcement of prescribed burns in NSW national parks.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Ongoing political and social debate has surrounded many aspects of the 2019–20 Australian fire crisis, particularly regarding the causes and future prevention of such fire activity, and the role of climate change.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The governing Liberal and National parties, accompanied by numerous news outlets associated with climate change denial, firmly deflected responsibility away from the record-breaking drought affecting the country and its associated links to climate change observations and projections.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Conversely, scientific experts have asserted the influence of climate change, drought, prolonged fire weather, and contextualized the limited role of prescribed burning and arson in influencing the crisis.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The political and social response to the crisis has been marked notably by political blame shifting, the circulation of large amounts of disinformation, and political disregard for scientific research, expert opinion, and previous government inquiries.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Further controversy has surrounded Prime Minister Scott Morrison for taking an overseas family holiday to Hawaiʻi, during the bushfires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] These criticisms also applied to New South Wales Minister for Emergency Services David Elliot, who went for a holiday in Europe.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Queensland Premier Annastacia Palaszczuk was also criticised for holidaying on a cruise ship while fires were active in the state.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] While travelling throughout fire-affected towns in New South Wales, Morrison was filmed attempting to shake the hands of two residents in Cobargo who had refused to shake his outstretched hand.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Morrison was criticised for grabbing and then shaking their hands despite their refusals.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] In an interview with Andrew Constance, NSW Liberal MP for Bega, Constance described the incident stating "the locals probably gave him the welcome he probably deserved".
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Morrison did not appear concerned with the criticism, later stating, "people are angry, and if people want to direct that at me, that is up to them".
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 4 January, volunteer firefighter Paul Parker, from Nelligen, rose to fame after he stopped his firetruck next to a Channel 7 news crew, and used colourful language to denounce what he perceived as an inadequate response by Morrison.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The video became viral over the following days.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Soon after, Morrison released a video on behalf of the Liberal Party regarding deployment of military assets to respond to the bushfire crisis, for which he was widely criticised.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Morrison was further criticised for a "donate" button on a Liberal Party website page which misleadingly led to a donations page for the Liberal Party itself, rather than bushfire relief; the button was later removed.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Philanthropists, corporate organisations, celebrities, and sportspeople donated to various fundraising appeals for bushfire victims and firefighters; estimated to total A$500 million as of 19 January 2020.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Following a representative sample, a report issued by the Fundraising Institute of Australia estimated that 53 percent of all adult Australians donated to a bushfire appeal.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Andrew Forrest and his wife, Nicola, donated A$70 million; and the Paul Ramsay Foundation donated A$30 million.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] In November, James Packer pledged A$1 million to support the NSWRFS.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] As the impact of the bushfire season spread, the Crown Resorts Foundation and the Packer Family Foundation pledged a further A$4 million to volunteer fire services in NSW, Victoria and Western Australia – all states in which Crown has resorts.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The Murdoch family donated A$5 million; the Micky and Madeleine Arison Family Foundation, A$1.5 million; and donations of A$1 million each were received from the Pratt Foundation, John and Pauline Gandel, Mike Cannon-Brookes, Scott Farquhar, and the Haines and the Perich families.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Leonardo DiCaprio donated US$3 million (A$3.4 million) via Earth Alliance; Kylie Jenner, US$1 million; Ellen DeGeneres, A$1.5 million; and donations of A$1 million were received from Sir Elton John and Chris Hemsworth and family.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The Wiggles performed a concert on 17 and 18 January, and on 16 February at Stadium Australia in Sydney, the Fire Fight Australia concert will feature local and international acts.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Tennis players, led by Nick Kyrgios, pledged to donate money for every ace served during the Australian summer of tennis.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Many cricket players, such as international representatives Chris Lynn, Glenn Maxwell, D'Arcy Short, Matthew Renshaw and Fawad Ahmed pledged to donate money for every wicket and/or six during the remainder of the Australian cricket season.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Shane Warne and Jeff Thomson, retired Australian cricketers, donated their baggy green Test cricket caps and Thomson also donated a playing vest for online auction.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Warne's cap was purchased by the Commonwealth Bank with a bid of A$1,007,500; and Russell Crowe's Rabbitohs cap was auctioned with a winning bid in excess of A$500,000.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Footballer Mathew Ryan, goalkeeper for Premier League club Brighton & Hove Albion and the Australia national team announced he'll donate $500 for every registered save by an English Premier League goalkeeper on the weekend of 11–12 January 2020.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Australian stars who were playing in the 2019–20 NBA season collectively donated in excess of A$1 million; and Lewis Hamilton, a Formula One driver, donated US$500,000.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Comedian Celeste Barber launched a fundraising appeal with a target of raising A$15,000, however it went on to raise over A$50 million, making it the largest fundraiser ever held on Facebook.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A telethon conducted with the Sydney New Year's Eve fireworks raised more than A$2 million.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Multiple media outlets reported that the Australian Competition and Consumer Commission (ACCC) received 86 reports of bushfire-related scams.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] It came as increased requests for cash driven donations leveraging crowdfunding platforms like GoFundMe, or as a result of false links posted on Twitter.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] It prompted some organisations to provide a list of approved and vetted charities online to reduce fraud.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] With 2,520 fires burning 978,519 acres (395,993 ha) of land, the 2020 wildfire season was the largest wildfire season in the US state of Arizona since 2011.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] Wildfires occur year-round in the state but are most numerous and typically burn the largest swaths of land during spring and summer.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] Peak fire season in the Southwest typically runs from May, when conditions are windy, hot, and dry, through mid-July, when the North American Monsoon provides the region with precipitation to slow fire activity.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] By the end of the year, more than fifty fires larger than 1,000 acres (400 ha) had burned within the state.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] However, the most notable fire of the season, the Ocotillo Fire, burned only 980 acres (400 ha) over four days and threatened the town of Cave Creek.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] It destroyed 20 buildings, including 8 homes.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] Historically, while "fire season" in Arizona began in April in desert areas and May around the Mogollon Rim with peak activities near July, there is now a fire risk year-round.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] Arizona is drought prone, with precipitation much different between the deserts and mountains.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] When the snow pack on the mountain melts, the moisture can reduce the risk of wildfire events.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] However, climate change can raise the snow line, reduce snow pack, decrease runoff, or cause earlier snowmelt.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] A risk of decreasing precipitation and dry monsoons could heighten fire risks.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] Heavy rainfall can allow vegetation to grow, and many of these plants quickly dry out in just hours.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] In April, the Arizona Department of Forestry and Fire Management expected a "potentially active" fire season reminiscent of the 2019 season.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] Increased grass load from a wet winter is expected to contribute to an elevated risk of fire in the Central Arizona deserts.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] Southwest Coordination Center Predictive Services forecasted an Above Normal risk for significant wildland fires from May through July for most of Arizona (excepting the Colorado Plateau), with fire potential returning to Normal by August with the arrival of a climatologically average monsoon.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] They cited above normal fine fuel loading in southern Arizona deserts and an active weather pattern through mid-June to support this risk.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] A fire department helicopter crashed while bringing supplies to firefighters, killing the pilot.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-arizona-wildfires] The following is a list of fires that burned more than 1,000 acres (400 ha), or produced significant structural damage or casualties.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] The **2020 Brazil rainforest wildfires** were a series of forest fires that were affecting Brazil, with 44,013 outbreaks of fires registered between January and August in the Amazonas and Pantanal.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] Within the Amazon, 6,315 outbreaks of fire were detected in the same period.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] Within the Pantanal, the volume of fires is equivalent to those of the past six years and there have been actions by NGOs and volunteers to save endangered animals, such as the jaguar.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] It was expected that the health systems of the Amazon region, already overloaded by the COVID-19 pandemic, would be even more overloaded due to respiratory diseases due to smoke emitted by the wildfires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] Expertise carried out points out that the fires in the Pantanal were started by human action and the Environmental Police Station investigates who are possibly responsible.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] Douglas Morton, head of NASA's Biospheric Sciences Laboratory, considers fires to be "unprecedented".
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] Although the Brazilian government has instituted a 120-day ban on burning in the Amazon, an analysis led by NASA indicates that this was of little effect.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] Between May 28 and August 25, 516 fire points were detected covering an area of 376,416 hectares.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] In August, President Jair Bolsonaro's response was that "the media and foreign governments are presenting a false narrative about the Amazon".
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] The same month Brazil's National Institute for Space Research reported that satellite data shows that the number of fires in the Amazon increased by 28% to ~6,800 fires in July compared to the ~5,300 wildfires in July 2019.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] This indicated a, potentially worsened, repeat of 2019's accelerated destruction of one of the world's largest protectable buffers against global warming in 2020.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] Satellites in September recorded 32,017 hotspots in the world's largest rainforest, a 61% rise from the same month in 2019.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] In September INPE reported that 1,359 km2 of the Brazilian Amazon have burned off in August, which may put the effectiveness of the contemporary response against the deforestation – such as considerations of economic interventions and the current military operation – into question.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] The 6,087 km2 of lost rainforest in 2020 as of early September – ~95% of the period in 2019 – is about the size of Palestine.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] In the Pantanal, part of the fire started in private areas or legal reserves (which is protected by law) and spread to indigenous territories.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] On 13 September preliminary data based on satellite images, indicate that 1.5 million hectares have burned in the Pantanal region since the start of August, surpassing the previous fire season record from 2005.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-brazil-rainforest-wildfires] On September 15 it was reported that 23,500 km2 – ~12% of the Pantanal – have burned off in 2020, killing millions of vertebrates.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] 2020 was a record-setting year for wildfires in California.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] Over the course of the year, 8,648 fires burned 4,304,379 acres (1,741,920 ha), more than four percent of the state's roughly 100 million acres of land, making 2020 the largest wildfire season recorded in California's modern history.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] However, it is roughly equivalent to the pre-1800 levels which averaged around 4.4 million acres yearly and up to 12 million in peak years.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] California's August Complex fire has been described as the first "gigafire", burning over 1 million acres across seven counties, an area larger than the state of Rhode Island.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] The fires destroyed over 10,000 structures and cost over $12.079 billion (2020 USD) in damages, including over $10 billion in property damage and $2.079 billion in fire suppression costs.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] The intensity of the fire season has been attributed to a combination of more than a century of poor forest management and higher temperatures resulting from climate change.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] On August 18, 2020, Governor Gavin Newsom declared a state of emergency, and on August 19, 2020, reported that the state was battling 367 known fires, many sparked by intense thunderstorms on August 16–17 caused by moisture from the remnants of Tropical Storm Fausto.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] Response and evacuations were complicated by a historic heatwave and the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] On August 22, 2020, President Donald Trump issued a major disaster declaration (DR-4558), which provides Individual Assistance and/or Public Assistance.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] In early September 2020, a combination of a record-breaking heat wave and strong katabatic winds (including the Jarbo, Diablo, and Santa Ana), caused explosive fire growth.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] The August Complex became California's largest recorded wildfire.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] The Creek Fire expanded in the Big Creek drainage area, temporarily trapping hundreds of campers near the Mammoth Pool Reservoir.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] The North Complex explosively grew in size as the winds fanned it westward, threatening the city of Oroville, triggering mass evacuations, and causing 16 fatalities.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] Governor Newsom's request for a federal disaster declaration for six major wildfires was approved on October 17, 2020 after having been rejected the previous day by the Trump administration.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] The timing of "fire season" in California is variable, depending on the amount of prior winter and spring precipitation, the frequency and severity of weather such as heat waves and wind events, and moisture content in vegetation.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] Northern California typically sees wildfire activity between late spring and early fall, peaking in the summer with hotter and drier conditions.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] Occasional cold frontal passages can bring wind and lightning.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] The timing of fire season in Southern California is similar, peaking between late spring and fall.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] The severity and duration of peak activity in either part of the state is modulated in part by weather events: downslope/offshore wind events can lead to critical fire weather, while onshore flow and Pacific weather systems can bring conditions that hamper wildfire growth.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] Early in the year, there was a concern for the 2020 fire season to potentially be prolonged and especially grave, due to the unusually dry months of January and February, one of the driest such periods of any calendar year on record.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] On March 22, 2020, a state of emergency was declared by California Governor Gavin Newsom due to a mass die-off of trees throughout the state, potentially increasing the risk of wildfires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] However, throughout March and April, rain began to consistently fall in the state, which alleviated the drought conditions.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] Despite this, Northern California was still expected to have severe wildfire conditions due to the moderate or severe drought conditions in the area, whereas Central and Southern California were expected to have serious fire conditions later in the year due to the late wet season and precipitation.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] On June 18, 2020, climate scientist Daniel Swain predicted the 2020 Arizona wildfire season was a sign of what was to come in California, due to similar drought and weather conditions between Arizona and Northern California.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] The year 2020 was the largest wildfire year recorded in California history, according to the California Department of Forestry and Fire Protection.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] From a historical perspective, the average annual acres burned prior to 1850 were probably significantly larger than years since reliable fire records began.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] Scott Stephens, a professor of fire science at UC Berkeley, estimated that prior to 1850, about 4,500,000 acres (1,800,000 ha) burned yearly, in fires that lasted for months.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] Activity peaked roughly every 30 years, with up to 11,800,000 acres (4,800,000 ha) burning during peak years.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] The indigenous peoples of California historically set controlled burns and allowed natural fires to run their course.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] The peak of the wildfire season usually occurs between July and November when hot, dry winds are most frequent.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] The wildfire season typically does not end until the first significant rainstorm of autumn arrives, which is usually around October in Northern California, and early November in Southern California.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] As wildfire becomes more frequent, the wildland–urban interface has increasingly become more dangerous when it comes to property damage and risk to life.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] Scientists believe that, prior to development, California fires regularly burned significantly more acreage than has been seen in recent history.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] Wildfires have been aggressively suppressed in recent years, resulting in a buildup of fuel, increasing the risk of large uncontrollable fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] There is broad scientific consensus that there should be more controlled burning of forests in California in order to reduce fire risk.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] A 2020 ProPublica investigation blames a combination of climate change and a history of insufficient controlled burning for the increase in "megafires." A sharp increase in the population and development of fire-prone areas has also contributed to the increase in flammable tinder.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] Climate change increases the temperature of wildfires in California, the risk for drought, and potentially also the frequency of such events.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] David Romps, director of the Berkeley Atmospheric Sciences Center summarizes the situation as follows: "To cut to the chase: Were the heat wave and the lightning strikes and the dryness of the vegetation affected by global warming?
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] Were they made significantly hotter, more numerous, and drier because of global warming?
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] Similarly, Friederike Otto, acting director of the University of Oxford Environmental Change Institute states, "There is absolutely no doubt that the extremely high temperatures are higher than they would have been without human-induced climate change.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] A huge body of attribution literature demonstrates now that climate change is an absolute game-changer when it comes to heat waves, and California won't be the exception." Susan Clark, director of the Sustainability Initiative at the University at Buffalo argues, "This is climate change.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] The National Interagency Fire Center's (NFIC) National Interagency Coordination (NICC) reported that monthly outlooks for the entire country will still drive wildfires across the country but especially California.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] The main drivers through fall and winter seasons will be La Nina, and drought conditions are going to continue through California, causing the wildfires to continue.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] The shift will start from Northern California to Southern California as precipitation will lessen the impact of wildfires across northern California.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] In August 2020, a suspect was charged by the Monterey County Sheriff with arson relating to the Dolan Fire; however, this has not been officially determined as the cause of the fire.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] In April 2021, another suspect, already arrested and charged for the murder of a woman, was charged with arson relating to the Markley Fire, one of the wildfires involving in the LNU Lightning Complex fires; according to authorities, the fire was set to cover up the aforementioned murder.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] Arson has also been suspected as the cause of the Ranch 2 Fire in Los Angeles County.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] A 2023 study found that these wildfires are affecting the California ecosystem and disrupting the habitats.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] It found that in the 2020 and 2021 fire seasons 58% of the area affected by wildfires occurred in those two seasons since 2012.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] These two fires destroyed 30% of the habitat of 50 species as well as 100 species that had 10% of their habitats burn.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] 5-14% of the species' habitats burned at a "high severity."Over 19000 sq.kms of vegetation burned affecting the habitat of more than 508 vertebrate species.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-california-wildfires] A study based on patient data between July and December 2020 found an association between the exposure to wildfire smoke with increased odds of ED visits for mental health conditions.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] The **2020 Chernobyl exclusion zone wildfires** were a series of wildfires that began burning inside Ukraine's Chernobyl exclusion zone in April 2020.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] The fires were largely extinguished within two weeks.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] At least one suspect was arrested for alleged arson.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] On April 6, radiation levels inside the zone were "16 times above normal" because of the fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] As the fire spread, a small village near the mostly abandoned town of Poliske was evacuated on April 10.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] By April 13, the wildfires had spread to just over 1.5 km (1 mi) away from the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant and had reached the outskirts of the abandoned city of Pripyat.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] More than 300 firefighters worked to stop the fires from reaching the plant.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] By 11 April, the firefighters had reached close to 400, with many helicopters and 100 fire engines dispersed to the Chernobyl exclusion zone.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] The State Emergency Service of Ukraine said it was still fighting the fires, but that the situation was under control, while Greenpeace said the situation was "much worse than Ukrainian authorities believe", citing satellite images.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] On 14 April, the State Emergency Service of Ukraine said all large fires inside the Exclusion Zone had been extinguished after ten days of firefighting efforts and recent rainfall in the region.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] According to Euro News, 124 firefighters were reported to have engaged the larger fire in Kotovsky Forest close to the village of Volodymyrivka.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] A 27-year-old local resident was arrested for arson.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] It is unclear if the man, who has confessed to starting fires "for fun", is partly or fully responsible for the wildfires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] The suspect told the authorities that he had set fire to dry grass close to the forest, without making an attempt to put out the fire as it started spreading.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] Fines for arson have been raised, after a vote by the parliament on 13 April.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] It was reported by a Forbes.com contributor that 30% of the tourist attractions in the exclusion zone had been destroyed, including the Soviet-era pioneer camp Izumrudnoe.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] The damage included several abandoned villages such as "Stara Markivka" surrounding Chernobyl that burnt down completely.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] Fire damage was also reported in the surrounding Red Forest where numerous trees were "swiftly" killed.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] The power plant itself, and the cities of Chernobyl and Pripyat survived "unscathed".
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] President Volodymyr Zelensky disclosed on 26 April that the fires had ravaged about 11.5 thousand hectares.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] The wildfires caused a thick haze to blanket the capital Kyiv, making its air pollution among the worst in the world, comparable with that of some Chinese cities.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] IQAir reported that, at one point on April 16, Kyiv had the worst air pollution in the world.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] However, the smog has had little impact on the health of residents as it coincided with a lockdown due to the COVID-19 pandemic in Ukraine, which meant most people were indoors.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] On 17 April, despite the increase in radiation levels the United Nations atomic agency stated that the power plant does not pose a danger to human health, considering the reports issued by Ukraine.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-chernobyl-exclusion-zone-wildfires] They also added that the concentration of radioactive materials in the air had stayed under the safety norms of Ukraine’s radiation, as discovered by the State Nuclear Regulatory Inspectorate of Ukraine.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-colorado-wildfires] The **2020 Colorado wildfire season** was a series of significant wildfires that burned throughout the U.S. state of Colorado as part of the 2020 Western United States wildfire season.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-colorado-wildfires] With a total of 665,454 acres (269,300 ha) burned, and the 3 largest fires in state history, it is Colorado's largest wildfire season on record.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-colorado-wildfires] During this season, the Cameron Peak Fire burned 208,913 acres, making it the largest wildfire recorded in the state of Colorado after it surpassed the Pine Gulch Fire, which earned the title seven weeks prior.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-colorado-wildfires] Also surpassing the Pine Gulch Fire in size was the East Troublesome Fire, which, when fully contained on November 30, had burned a total of 193,812 acres.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-colorado-wildfires] In total, the suppression costs for the fires during the 2020 season amounted to at least $266 million (2020 USD).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-colorado-wildfires] Throughout the year thousands of people were forced to evacuate, including the whole town of Estes Park during the East Troublesome fire.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-colorado-wildfires] Air quality was poor as well through much of the fire season, especially during the Cameron Peak and East Troublesome fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-colorado-wildfires] While "fire season" varies every year based on different weather conditions, most wildfires occur between May and September with a fire risk year-round with an increasing danger during winter.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-colorado-wildfires] Drought and decreasing snowpack levels and lowering snowmelt and runoff increase fire risk.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-colorado-wildfires] These conditions, along with increased temperatures and decreased humidity, are becoming more common from climate change.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-colorado-wildfires] Vegetation growth provides an ample fuel for fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-colorado-wildfires] From 2011 to 2020, Colorado experiences an average of 5,618 wildfires each year that collectively burn about 237,500 acres (96,100 ha).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] The **2020 Córdoba wildfires** are a series of wildfires burning through the Córdoba Province in Argentina.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] Over 60,000 hectares (150,000 acres) are estimated to have been affected by the fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] Fifty-one fires had been registered as of October 2020.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] Residents of several towns had to be evacuated.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] At least two persons died as a consequence of the fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] Provincial Justice started an investigation on the wildfires, suspecting they were started intentionally in some areas.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] Argentina was affected by several wildfires in 2020, during a pronounced drought, such as the 2020 Delta del Paraná wildfires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] The center Argentine region, primarily the Córdoba Province, has a temperate climate with a low-humidity winter.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] Rainfall season is limited to the spring and summer, while winters usually lack rains.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] This has been changing to a more humid climate, according to some opinions, due to climate change.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] During August 2020, the center region of Argentina experienced a drought, aggravated by an increase in winds, which favored the spread of wildfires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] Particularly, the Sierras de Córdoba Mountains Range went by over 100 days without rains, with temperatures reaching 39 °C (102 °F).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] The El Niño–Southern Oscillation phenomenon was, by September 2020, in a neutral phase, with an increase of a La Niña phenomenon likelihood.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] The Córdoba vegetation cover is composed of "native mount" species—trees such as *Prosopis* (Spanish: *algarrobos*), pepper trees (*molles*), desert hackberries (*talas*), espinillos, and quebrachos—thorny shrubs, and in mountain areas grasslands with dry grasses.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] This vegetation is a big combustion risk during the dry season.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] Winter months usually harbor the most wildfires, with August being the month with the largest number of fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] In the 21st century, the largest number of fires was registered in 2003, with 364 fires, and the biggest affected areas being recorded in 2013, with 106,206 hectares (262,440 acres).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] 95% of wildfires in Argentina are a consequence of human action, some intentional and others caused by neglect or carelessness after bonfires, the dropping of cigarette butts, or the burning of trash getting out of control.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] Some intentional fires are believed to have been started by ranchers to clean pastures for further agricultural or husbandry usage of lands, and others for real state use, such as the construction of gated communities.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] Park rangers volunteered to help fight the fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] As of 1 October, seven planes were being used (6 hydrant and 1 for support), and 200 brigadiers were deployed to fight the fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] Authorities had to insist on advising residents to not try to control the fires themselves, as they sometimes blocked roads while trying to do so, disturbing the firemen's work.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] Some volunteer firefighters claimed neighbors should be trained to help fight the fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] The environmental damage of the fires was deemed "unmeasurable", citing a biodiversity loss as well as a lowered catchment capacity of soils.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] As the fires extend, an increased likelihood of future fires is expected in areas burnt in 2020.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] As the Córdoba Mountains' vegetation is of slow growth, between 5 and 20 centimetres a year, about 30 years are expected to be needed for the forests to recover.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] Up to a 48% decrease in water capture is expected to hit the basins surrounding the burnt areas.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] Mountain creeks are used for human water consumption, and are already affected by droughts.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] They could drag ashes and burnt material, affecting drinkable water quality.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-córdoba-wildfires] An agricultural state of emergency was declared in the affected areas, and relief packages were established.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] The **2020 Delta del Paraná wildfires** is a series of wildfires that are burning across the Delta del Paraná in Argentina, affecting mainly the Entre Ríos and Santa Fe provinces, but also Buenos Aires, including major cities as Rosario.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] The first outbreaks were detected in February 2020, and new ones keep emerging until August 2020 at least.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] Previously, this same area had suffered the 2008 Delta del Paraná wildfires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] A 10 million pesos (US$137,934) daily cost was estimated.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] During the first months of 2020, the Río de la Plata river basin received an unusually low amount of rain, including the Iguazú and Paraguay rivers.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] This even caused the Iguazú Falls to dry for a time, what created a diplomatic conflict between Argentina and Brazil, over the several dams the country operates in the northern area of the basin.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] Brazil ultimately decided to open the floodgates of the dam for 12 days on 18 May 2020.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] This drought, which conjugated with the La Niña phenomenon, brought an historical low for the Paraná river level (the lowest level in 51 years).
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] Every watercourse in the De la Plata river basin registered very low levels and droughts, caused by rainfall anomalies in the northern area of the basin.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] This low water level caused several problems, including trouble for big ships to navigate and export the harvest, water intakes in several cities unable to soak any water, and a big fish mortality.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] It also made several environment-harming activities easier, such as illegal fishing and hunting, activities which in some cases involve engaging in illegal fires as well.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] But mainly, this lack of rainfalls caused a drought in the Delta del Paraná, and a lack of moisture in its abundant available plant biomass that stimulates the start and fast expansion of fires.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] During the summer, it was thought that the fires could be caused by people putting out cigarettes or leaving bonfires lit while on the Delta del Paraná islands, as well as by cattle ranchers trying to gain terrain.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] Meanwhile, during 2020 farmers and ranchers in Argentina were subject of several kinds of sabotages, including silobolsas being shattered and fields set into fire.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] The agricultural sector pointed that the fires were a consequence of the higher amount of public visiting the islands (both tourists and poachers), the high number of available plant biomass, and even some political intentionality, linked to the sabotaged suffered by them during the year.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] Criminal charges were brought against several ranchers.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] On the other hand, several Environmental organizations pointed that the fires were started by ranchers to renew graze, as they do every year, but with the difference that in 2020 the drought made those fires bigger and easier to grow, which caused the shift so rapidly.
[src:2020-colorado-wildfires/2020-delta-del-paraná-wildfires] The government credited this theory, blaming the fires on ranchers.
